The atoll sign, also known as the "ring around the lagoon" sign, is a radiological finding that can be seen on computed tomography (CT) scans of the lungs. It is characterized by a ring-like appearance surrounding a central area of low attenuation, resembling an atoll. This sign is typically associated with pulmonary alveolar proteinosis (PAP), a rare lung disease in which there is an abnormal accumulation of surfactant-like protein and phospholipids within the alveoli. The atoll sign is considered a specific and sensitive indicator of PAP, although it can also be seen in other conditions such as pulmonary edema, pneumonia, and lymphangitic carcinomatosis.
